Reducing GFRN Gene Lists for Nanostring

David Jenkins

4/10/2017

Optimized Pathways

The GFRN Pathways Optimized in the Genome Medice Paper are as follows:

knitr::kable(print_corr_df(results[1096704,]))

The seven pathway signatures contain a total of 980 genes, but because of overlapping genes in the signatures there are a total of 759 unique genes in this set of signatures.

To port these signatures onto the nanostring, we want to reduce the number of unique probes that are needed for this set of signatures. For example, here are the correlations if all signatures had 10 genes (54 unique genes):

knitr::kable(compare_two_corrs(results[1096704,], results[70958,]))

Reduce by Summed Correlation

If we sum the correlation to each of the proteins of interest, the optimized pathway list has a total correlation of 14.8795. We can compare this summed correlation to the summed correlation values for all smaller pathway list correlations (there are a total of 1 million possible smaller gene list combinations based on the ASSIGn results calculated during pathway optimizations:)
